            <Text>NATIONAL NOVEL WRITING MONTH TEMPLATE

#	￼

Before You Begin
It's that time of the year again! Thanks for choosing to make Scrivener part of your novel-writing adventure this year. Although you can just dive in and start using Scrivener straight away, to get the most out of the program we recommend taking a look at some of the following resources before you begin writing:

Tutorial:	An interactive tutorial is available from the Help menu in Scrivener. This is a Scrivener project that walks you through all of the main features of Scrivener as you use it. It’s thorough and takes a couple of hours to go through, but once you’ve finished it you’ll be well on your way to becoming a Scrivener expert, and will be able to decide which tools will work best for you.

Videos:	We have a range of tutorial videos available on our website at http://www.literatureandlatte.com/videos. A ten-minute introductory video that whisks through Scrivener’s main features and is ideal for getting started can be found here:
	http://www.literatureandlatte.com/videos/ScrivIntroLarge.mov
	A smaller version is available here:
	http://www.literatureandlatte.com/videos/ScrivIntroSmall.mov

Help File:	I know, no one likes reading the Help file, but you may want to take a look at the “Quick Start” guide in the Help PDF file, which you can view by selecting “Scrivener Manual” from the “Help” menu.

About This Template
This template has been designed to provide some useful tools for your daily writing sessions, and a few general writing tools for novelists, such as character sketches and document labels. At the end of the month, you will want to compile (File > Compile) your novel for export. When you do so, you'll have several "Format As" choices, one of which is unique to this release. The two you will find most useful for NaNoWriMo are as follows:

1.	Novel (Standard Manuscript Format): when compiled (File > Compile), this project will generate a document in the standard manuscript format for novels. If you think you have a winner on your hands, this will get you submission-ready in no time at all.
2.	NaNoWriMo (Obfuscated): this compile method will produce a plain-text file suitable for uploading to the NaNoWriMo.org servers, with garbled text so that it has the correct word-count but is no longer legible. It is also optimised to reduce any extra words getting included in your count (for instance from the title page) that might result from some of the more fancy compile options. (Note that this exporter will give the best results with English works, but should do well with most Latin-based languages; to tweak the results, visit the Replacements panel in the Compile sheet.)

What This Template Provides
Project Targets have already been set up for you (Project > Show Project Targets). You can keep this open as you write and watch the bars fill up. The daily session goal has been set for the optimum number of words you should write each day to reach 50,000 words by the end of November. If you are using a different, personally-set goal, you can change these numbers—if so, you'll probably want to change the document goal in the Template Sheets/Daily Target file, too.

How To Use this Template
	•	Edit the Title Page document to ensure it contains the correct information. If you don't have a title yet, you can leave this blank for now.
	•	Some useful links have been provided in the Project References, which you can get to by clicking on the little stack of books at the bottom of the Inspector to your right, and selecting Project References instead of Document References from the title bar above the references list.
	•	Create a new folder for each chapter and title each folder with the name of the chapter. If you don’t intend to use chapter names, just use something descriptive that tells you what the chapter is about. (You do not need to title the folders “Chapter One” and so on, as chapter numbering will be taken care of automatically during the Compile process.) The first chapter folder has been created for you with the placeholder title “Chapter”.
	•	Create a new text document for each scene inside the chapter folders. (When using the standard submission compile format, scenes will be separated with the “#” character.)
	•	If you want to keep track of your daily writing by creating a new file for each day’s work, select “Daily Target” from the Project > New From Template menu at the start of the day to create a new document. This will create a blank document that has already been set up with a word-count goal of 1,667 words (if you write that many words every day, you will reach the target of 50,000 words after 30 days). As you write, you can watch the progress bar in the footer area fill up as you approach your goal.
	•	Information about characters can be placed in the “Characters” folder, and information about locations can be placed in the “Places” folder. (These are just regular folders that have had custom icons assigned to them using the Documents > Change Icon feature.)
	•	Character and setting sketch sheets have been provided which can be used for filling out information about the people and places in your novel. These are located in the “Template Sheets” folder. You should not edit the documents in the “Template Sheets” folder directly unless you wish to change the templates (which you are free to do - you may wish to customise the sketch sheets or get rid of them entirely). Instead, to create a new character sheet, click on the Characters folder (or wherever you want to create your new character sheet) and from the Project menu, select New From Template > Character Sketch. This creates a new character sketch document for you to edit and fill in with your character details. You can create setting sketch sheets in the same way.

Remember that only the text of documents contained inside the “Manuscript” folder counts towards your word count, so you can place support materials and make notes anywhere else.

Making Changes
There are various minor changes you can make to the settings to tweak this template so that it better suits your needs, as follows:
	•	Chapter subtitles: If you don’t want to include the names of your chapter folders below the chapter numbering text in the compiled document, go to the “Formatting” pane in the Compile sheet and deselect “Title” in the list of elements to include.
	•	Page header: You can edit the page header in the “Page Settings” pane of the Compile sheet.
	•	Working with chapters instead of scenes: By default, this project is set up so that you write each scene as a separate text document. If you don’t like to break things up quite that much and would prefer to write an entire chapter in each text document, make the following changes:
	1.	Rename the “Scene” document to use your chapter title and move it so that it is directly below the “Title Page” document.
	2.	Move the “Chapter” folder to the Trash.
	3.	Create a new text document for each chapter.
	4.	In the “Separators” pane of the Compile sheet, change the “Text separator” setting to “Page break”.

Note that if you make extensive changes to the Compile settings, you may wish to save your export settings before switching to the NaNo exporter by using the “Save…” button in the Compile sheet.

Sample Document
See the “Sample MS” PDF file in the Research folder for an example of a document that has been created using this template.

Final Note
Scrivener project templates are flexible and are not intended to restrict you to a particular workflow. You can change, delete or move the files and folders contained in the template, and you can create your own templates by setting up a skeletal project with the files, folders and settings you would like to use for new projects and using File > Save As Template. The version of Scrivener you are currently using is a preview of our 2.0 release, and there will be many more project templates available in the release version.

That's it! We wish you the best of luck on reaching your goal this year, and remember that if you win, you will receive a coupon which can be used to buy Scrivener for only 50% of the regular price. This coupon can be used for the Mac version, or the Windows version when it goes on sale in early 2011.
	—Literature &amp; Latte Team</Text>
